day blog post too, here ",[560,561,563],"a",{"href":562},"\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002FKubeCon-Copenhagen-2018-Day-1.md","KubeCon Copenhagen 2018 Day 1",".",[552,566,568],{"id":567},"morning-keynotes","Morning Keynotes",[570,571,573],"h3",{"id":572},"keynote-kubernetes-project-update-aparna-sinha-group-product-manager-kubernetes-and-google-kubernetes-engine-google","Keynote: Kubernetes Project Update - Aparna Sinha, Group Product Manager, Kubernetes and Google Kubernetes Engine, Google",[529,575,576,581],{},[577,578],"img",{"alt":579,"src":580},"KubeCon - Keynote - Kubernetes Major Milestones","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_090849.jpg","\nKubernetes Major Milestones",[529,583,584],{},"The following points are currently especially important for enterprises:",[586,587,588,592,595],"ol",{},[589,590,591],"li",{},"Security",[589,593,594],{},"Applications",[589,596,597],{},"Experience",[599,600,591],"h4",{"id":601},"security",[529,603,604],{},[577,605],{"alt":606,"src":607},"KubeCon - Keynote - Kubernetes Security Progress","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_091152.jpg",[529,609,610,611,617],{},"On GKE they made updates seamless.\n\"Old\" points are awaking for Kubernetes like Threat detection.\nGKE integrates with a good amount of security\u002Ftreat detections to make the platform safer.\nUpcoming from SIG container is sandboxed containers. To get a \"full\" sandboxed container, you should use a hypervisor. Still the users want the low resource point of (normal) containers.\nGoogle has open sourced ",[560,612,616],{"href":613,"rel":614},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fgoogle\u002Fgvisor",[615],"nofollow","gVisor"," which is a sandboxed container runtime.",[529,619,620],{},[577,621],{"alt":622,"src":623},"KubeCon - Keynote - Sandboxed containers","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_091557.jpg",[599,625,594],{"id":626},"applications",[529,628,629],{},[577,630],{"alt":631,"src":632},"KubeCon - Keynote - Kubernetes Applications Progress","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_091823.jpg",[529,634,635],{},"Kubernetes has now an integration to be the scheduler for Apache Spark.\nTo automate stateful applications, it is recommended to use an operator.",[529,637,638],{},[577,639],{"alt":640,"src":641},"KubeCon - Keynote - Automating stateful applications","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_091934.jpg",[529,643,644,645,650],{},"In the demo Google's ",[560,646,649],{"href":647,"rel":648},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002FGoogleCloudPlatform\u002Fspark-on-k8s-operator",[615],"spark-operator"," was showcased.\nI recommend to checkout the recording, to see exactly what she showed.",[652,653,176],"h5",{"id":654},"monitoring",[529,656,657],{},[577,658],{"alt":659,"src":660},"KubeCon - Keynote - Kubernetes Monitoring","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_092435.jpg",[529,662,663],{},"Prometheus is the default monitoring\u002Fmetrics pipeline in Kubernetes.",[652,665,667],{"id":666},"developer-experience","Developer Experience",[529,669,670,671,676,677,680],{},"A Google Customer engineer developed ",[560,672,675],{"href":673,"rel":674},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002FGoogleContainerTools\u002Fskaffold",[615],"Skaffold"," which improves the developer experience for continuous integration + deployment.\nIn the end the developer just wants to \"run his code\".\nThe important part is that the developer can focus on the development.\n",[560,678,675],{"href":673,"rel":679},[615]," will pick up changes and automatically deploy it to Kubernetes (from what I think, especially for testing).",[570,682,684],{"id":683},"keynote-accelerating-kubernetes-native-applications-brandon-philips-cto-of-coreos-red-hat","Keynote: Accelerating Kubernetes Native Applications - Brandon Philips, CTO of CoreOS, Red Hat",[529,686,687],{},"The point of operators making it easy to deploy and manage applications is more and more important.",[529,689,690],{},[577,691],{"alt":692,"src":693},"KubeCon - Keynote - Operators: Kube Native Apps","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_093229.jpg",[529,695,696],{},"It is amazing to hear a success story such as that for an operator, as you normally just hear \"it works\" ;)",[529,698,699],{},[577,700],{"alt":701,"src":702},"KubeCon - Keynote - The Operator Framework","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_093315.jpg",[529,704,705],{},"They will release more components of the operator framework over the coming weeks.\nBut a point coming with with having more and more operators running is that you need a lifecycle management for operators in general.\nA lifecycle management in that point could be like a catalog of operators.",[570,707,709],{"id":708},"keynote-switching-horses-midstream-the-challenges-of-migrating-150-microservices-to-kubernetes-sarah-wells-technical-director-for-operations-and-reliability-financial-times","Keynote: Switching Horses Midstream: The Challenges of Migrating 150+ Microservices to Kubernetes - Sarah Wells, Technical Director for Operations and Reliability, Financial Times",[529,711,712],{},[577,713],{"alt":714,"src":715},"KubeCon - Keynote - This is what it really looks like","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_093852.jpg",[529,717,718],{},"If you are doing a thing such as \"live\" migration, it is as with every project a journey.",[529,720,721],{},[577,722],{"alt":723,"src":724},"KubeCon - Keynote - Metrics for success","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_094325.jpg",[529,726,727],{},"Their setup is very complex as they went completely for microservice architecture already.\nThey see innovation like a spending (innovation token).\nIn the end they reached a cost reduction in AWS of about ~80%.",[529,729,730],{},[577,731],{"alt":732,"src":733},"KubeCon - Keynote - Opted for Kubernetes","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_094326.jpg",[529,735,736],{},"They opted for Kubernetes, so they can ask other people about it as opposed to creating their own orchestration tool. With an own tool, you on your own need to know the documentation.",[526,738,739],{},[529,740,741],{},"\"You pay a cost when running services in parallel\"\n- Sarah Wells",[529,743,744],{},"It is always a risk, but risks are to be conquered if the advantages overweight the disadvantages.\nThey used traffic replay to test further and simply use their existing API to push to both stacks to test.",[526,746,747],{},[529,748,749],{},"\"Switching from systemd files to Helm\"\n- Sarah Wells",[529,751,752],{},"If you don't use Golang vendoring, you're gonna have a bad time when rebuilding a two year old project.",[529,754,755],{},[577,756],{"alt":757,"src":758},"KubeCon - Keynote - Shouldn't be too scared quote","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_094455.jpg",[529,760,761],{},"In their case they had a good amount of services already having a readiness and\u002For liveness \"interface\".",[526,763,764],{},[529,765,766],{},"\"Easy to get sucked into making things better\"\n- Sarah Wells",[526,768,769],{},[529,770,771],{},"\"It is worth mentioning the increase in bills to the people that pay the bills\"\n- Sarah Wells",[529,773,774],{},"The final migration went smooth for them mostly only issues arose because people used the platform in a way they didn't understand.",[529,776,777],{},[577,778],{"alt":779,"src":780},"KubeCon - Keynote - Healthcheck timeouts","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_095106.jpg",[529,782,783],{},"They broke even in about three years after their migration.",[529,785,786],{},[577,787],{"alt":788,"src":789},"KubeCon - Keynote - Reduction in hosting and support costs","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_095600.jpg",[526,791,792],{},[529,793,794,795,799,800,802],{},"\"",[796,797,798],"span",{},"...","a happier team",[796,801,798],{},"\"\n- Sarah Wells",[570,804,806],{"id":805},"keynote-shaping-the-cloud-native-future-abby-kearns-executive-director-cloud-foundry-foundation","Keynote: Shaping the Cloud Native Future - Abby Kearns, Executive Director, Cloud Foundry Foundation",[529,808,809],{},[577,810],{"alt":811,"src":812},"KubeCon - Keynote - Cloud Cobbling","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_100114.jpg",[529,814,815],{},"Everything is \"cobbling\" together a way for themselves to the cloud.",[529,817,818,822],{},[577,819],{"alt":820,"src":821},"KubeCon - Keynote - Trinity of Interoperability, Innovation and Velocity","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_100118.jpg","\nTrinity of Interoperability, Innovation and Velocity",[529,824,825],{},"A companies world increases with each software\u002Ftechnology they use.",[529,827,828],{},"TBH this is kind of the same as everyone is saying:",[830,831,832,835,838],"ul",{},[589,833,834],{},"OpenSource is cool",[589,836,837],{},"We have to get together (conferences, meetups, etc)",[589,839,840],{},"And so on..",[570,842,844],{"id":843},"keynote-skip-the-anxiety-attack-build-secure-apps-with-kubernetes-jason-mcgee-fellow-ibm","Keynote: Skip the Anxiety Attack - Build Secure Apps with Kubernetes, Jason McGee, Fellow, IBM",[529,846,847],{},"I wasn't at the keynote because I had checked out the CNCF booth for the \"Meet the Maintainer - Rook\" meetup.",[570,849,851],{"id":850},"keynote-softwares-community-dave-zolotusky-software-engineer-spotify","Keynote: Software's Community - Dave Zolotusky, Software Engineer, Spotify",[529,853,847],{},[552,855,857],{"id":856},"meet-the-maintainer-rook","Meet the Maintainer - Rook",[526,859,864,882,883],{"className":860,"dataLang":863},[861,862],"twitter-tweet","tw-align-center","en",[529,865,867,868,872,873,877,878],{"lang":863,"dir":866},"ltr","Hostile takeover of the ",[560,869,871],{"href":870},"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FCloudNativeFdn?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw","@CloudNativeFdn"," booth in progress ",[560,874,876],{"href":875},"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fhashtag\u002Fkubecon?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw","#kubecon"," ",[560,879,881],{"href":880},"https:\u002F\u002Ft.co\u002FB034FWvOgk","pic.twitter.com\u002FB034FWvOgk","— rook (@rook_io) ",[560,884,886],{"href":885},"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Frook_io\u002Fstatus\u002F991969884056768513?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw","May 3, 2018",[888,889],"script",{"async":890,"src":891,"charSet":892},true,"https:\u002F\u002Fplatform.twitter.com\u002Fwidgets.js","utf-8",[529,894,895],{},"It was nice meeting people interested in Rook.",[552,897,899],{"id":898},"talks","Talks",[570,901,903],{"id":902},"blackholes-and-wormholes-understand-and-troubleshoot-the-magic-of-kubernetes-networking-minhan-xia-rohit-ramkumar-google-intermediate-skill-level","Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Minhan Xia & Rohit Ramkumar, Google (Intermediate Skill Level)",[529,905,906],{},"Both talkers are \"the last line of defense\" for support cases.",[599,908,910],{"id":909},"blackhole-case","Blackhole Case",[529,912,913],{},"No backend receives a packet sent by another Pod after a endpoint change.",[529,915,916],{},[577,917],{"alt":918,"src":919},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Conntrack in a nutshell","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_140349.jpg",[529,921,922],{},[577,923],{"alt":924,"src":925},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Netfilter in a nutshell","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_140452.jpg",[529,927,928],{},"In this case, when the Service IP is called a conntrack entry is created when routed to Pod A. When a Pod is killed and the conntrack entries still exist, the traffic fails to get to the other Pods because of this.\nA fix for this has been implemented in kube-proxy. Kube-proxy flushes the conntrack table of stale entries now, though there might be a small delay\u002Floss for then incoming packets until \"everything\" has been refreshed.",[599,930,932],{"id":931},"yet-another-blackhole-case","Yet Another Blackhole Case",[529,934,935],{},[577,936],{"alt":937,"src":938},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Blackhole #2 - Explained","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_141040.jpg",[529,940,941,942,946,947,950],{},"This was caused due to OOM causing networkd to be restarted which then triggered a bug that reset the ",[943,944,945],"code",{},"forwarding"," sysctl setting for the main ethernet interface to ",[943,948,949],{},"0"," causing no more traffic to be forwarded to the container network bridge.",[599,952,954],{"id":953},"wormhole","Wormhole",[529,956,957],{},[577,958],{"alt":959,"src":960},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Wormhole Set up","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_141239.jpg",[529,962,963,964,967],{},"Because of Pod B on a node which exposes a ",[943,965,966],{},"hostPort"," that is the same as the Pod A, that is why the traffic is wormholed to Pod B.",[526,969,970],{},[529,971,972],{},"\"Iptables should be as explicit as possible.\"\n- Minhan Xia & Rohit Ramkumar",[599,974,207],{"id":975},"troubleshooting",[529,977,978],{},"Iptables is the first source of truth.",[529,980,981],{},[577,982],{"alt":983,"src":984},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - What's in my iptables?","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_141832.jpg",[529,986,987],{},"Each endpoint has it's own chain.",[529,989,990],{},"conntrack is also an important to see where the connection got \"tracked\" to.",[529,992,993],{},"tcpdump should be used to verify that a request\u002Fdata was actually sent from a Pod and\u002For received on another node.",[529,995,996],{},[577,997],{"alt":998,"src":999},"KubeCon - Talk - Blackholes and Wormholes: Understand and Troubleshoot the “Magic” of Kubernetes Networking - Conclusion","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_142456.jpg",[570,1001,1003],{"id":1002},"clusters-as-cattle-how-to-seamlessly-migrate-apps-across-kubernetes-clusters-andy-goldstein-heptio-intermediate-skill-level","Clusters as Cattle: How to Seamlessly Migrate Apps across Kubernetes Clusters - Andy Goldstein, Heptio (Intermediate Skill Level)",[529,1005,1006],{},[577,1007],{"alt":1008,"src":1009},"KubeCon - Talk - Clusters as Cattle: How to Seamlessly Migrate Apps across Kubernetes Clusters - Title","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_163243.jpg",[526,1011,1012],{},[529,1013,1014],{},"\"Tickets\nApprovals\nDelays\"\n- Andy Goldstein",[529,1016,1017],{},"Your server is your pet, when it is broken you want to fix it as fast as possible.",[529,1019,1020],{},"Kubernetes does the scheduling.",[526,1022,1023],{},[529,1024,1025],{},"\"Is a cluster a cattle or a pet?\"\n- Andy Goldstein",[529,1027,1028],{},[577,1029],{"alt":1030,"src":1031},"KubeCon - Talk - Clusters as Cattle: How to Seamlessly Migrate Apps across Kubernetes Clusters - K8s App Migrations","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_164429.jpg",[526,1033,1034],{},[529,1035,1036],{},"\"At one point every node will be decomissioned\"\n- Andy Goldstein",[529,1038,1039],{},"Overall in Kubernetes yout should not use IPs for Services. DNS names should be used instead.",[529,1041,1042],{},[577,1043],{"alt":1044,"src":1045},"KubeCon - Talk - Clusters as Cattle: How to Seamlessly Migrate Apps across Kubernetes Clusters - Routing Overview","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_165004.jpg",[529,1047,1048],{},"When migrating one could potentially use a setup such as this and use a separate Kubernetes cluster to do the routing of the internet traffic.",[529,1050,1051],{},"His demo showed the whole setup he explained.\nHe showcased the migration point from one to another cluster. This can potentially be also used for failover.\nAdditionally to that heptio\u002Fark's backup and restore was demonstrated with that.",[529,1053,1054],{},"Interesting to see the switch functionality between the clusters with a simple config change.",[552,1056,1058],{"id":1057},"all-attendee-party","All Attendee Party",[529,1060,1061,1065],{},[577,1062],{"alt":1063,"src":1064},"KubeCon - All Attendee Party - So many people!","\u002Fblog\u002F2018\u002Fkubecon-copenhagen-2018-day-2\u002Fimg_20180503_184245.jpg","\nSo many people!",[526,1067,1069,1081,1082],{"className":1068,"dataLang":863},[861,862],[529,1070,1071,1072,1074,1075,877,1077],{"lang":863,"dir":866},"The ",[560,1073,871],{"href":870}," has stepped up their game. This event rocks! A new normal for ",[560,1076,876],{"href":875},[560,1078,1080],{"href":1079},"https:\u002F\u002Ft.co\u002FhprNrJnK5V","pic.twitter.com\u002FhprNrJnK5V","— bassam (@bassamtabbara) ",[560,1083,886],{"href":1084},"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbassamtabbara\u002Fstatus\u002F992092821631877120?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw",[888,1086],{"async":890,"src":891,"charSet":892},[552,1088,1090],{"id":1089},"summary","Summary",[529,1092,1093],{},"The all attendee party was awesome! Looking forward to the next KubeCon all attendee party already.",[529,1095,1096],{},"Have Fun!",{"title":1098,"searchDepth":1099,"depth":1099,"links":1100},"",2,[1101,1102,1111,1112,1116,1117],